Hi - Nick Singh here from DataLemur/Ace the Data ScienceÂ Interview here to warn you about the mid-twit mental trap and how it's hurting your tech career.

It's related to those mid-twit IQ-bell curve memes... you've seen theseÂ before, right?Â 

IQ bell curve memes make fun of a commonplace phenomena:

**Â  Mid-IQs (mid-twits) complicate things.
Â  Dumb & Smart people keep shit simple.Â **

By the end of this email, you will:

* Realize the tech career advice you've internalized is likely for mid-twits

* Understand why influencers are incentivized to overcomplicate things

* Become more confident about advancing in your career (because things are actually simple, and the bar is stupidly low)

First, let's cover how we got into this mid-twit mess.

****Why Gurus Lead Us Into Mid-Twittery ****
Overly complicated mid-twit advice abounds not because it's correct or helpful.

It's because thought leaders have perverse incentives to lead us into mid-twittery.Â 

Gurus can't stand out on social media if they give generic, simple advice.

To compete, they differentiate themselves by complicating things in the hopes of capturing your attention.Â 

Similarly, influencers find it hard to monetize simplistic advice, because consumers don't pay for advice that'll fit on a single page.

That's why authors convolute basic concepts and write fluff in order to sell you a 200-page book.

This phenomenon is most obvious in the health & fitness world, where it's difficult to monetize the one-liner "

**eat less, exercise more**".

That's why every few years you'll see another contrived fad diet:

Simply put, for influencers it pays $ to dispense over-complicated advice to mid-twits.Â 

I know what you're probably thinking at this point...

Â 

****Nick you're a guru... and a hypocrite?!****
As someone with 155kÂ LinkedIn https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-kw08QGWqUP6XF5ytPL followers, 25k on Twitter https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-kx08QGWqUP6XF5ytPL, and a best-selling book on Data Science Interviews https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-ky08QGWqUP6XF5ytPL, you might think it's a bit hypocritical for me to call out tech influencers and career gurus since I sorta am one!

But I'd like to think my brand was built on dispensing simple, concrete, and mostly FREE advice like: * Go build portfolio projects https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-kz08QGWqUP6XF5ytPL

* Show off projects to hiring managers by sending cold emails https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-k008QGWqUP6XF5ytPL

* Go learn SQL by practicing real SQL interview questions https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-k108QGWqUP6XF5ytPL

Of course, if you think I'm guilty of dispensing overly-complicated advice, reply and let me know - I'm always looking for feedback on ways to make my tips simpler!Â 

Anyways, back to the main point for today: the bar is stupidly low, and honestly you don't need to follow overly complex advice to get ahead in your tech career.

****The Bar Is Shockingly Low****
Recently, I spoke at the Open Data Science Conference (ODSC) where I covered How to Ace the Data Job Hunt https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-k208QGWqUP6XF5ytPL for a crowd of 120 people.Â 

During the talk, something shocking happened, which made me realize just how low the bar was for job hunting.

I asked the audience:

Â  Â Â "On your resume, how 

**published**
Â  Â  Â is your portfolio project"?

2 people out of 120 had a proper URL to their project (ex. DataLemur.com)

5 people had a link to a repo (ex. github .com/NickSingh/DataLemur)

Surprised by how few people had resumes which linked to their project, I asked the 120 people a more basic question:

**Â  Â Â "Forget links. Who has a non-school,
Â  Â  Â individually done portfolio project
Â  Â  Â on your resume?"**

**Only 10ish more hands went up!Â **

Here I was, droning on and on about how to make a good portfolio project even more amazing by buying a domain name for it (ex. "BobReccomendsMovies.com").

Yet, 85% of the room didn't even have a single individually & independently finished project to their name!

Â 

This experience made me feel so dumb for giving advanced advice when most of the audience hadn't done the portfolio project basics!

Low Bar: Facebook Referrals
Another story of how low the bar is comes from 2018 when I judged a hackathon at the University of Virginia (my alma mater) on behalf of my employer, 

**Facebook**.

Over the course of the weekend, I gave 12 people my official @facebook.com email address since they asked for a referral.Â 

**ZERO** of them sent me an email asking for a referral within the next year!

I'm not even sure why I bother teaching people about 6 cold email rules to never break https://nicksingh79965.acemlna.com/lt.php?x=3TZy~GE6KaKfEHz-_Q1GUuRzAX-pvN-gkuovY5jMIFia5XKryEy.yuJr5X6imNE~j-k308QGWqUP6XF5ytPL when the majority of people won't even follow-up with someone they met IRL.Â 

Instead of recounting 894 more stories of how doing the basic stuff can get you ahead in your career, I'll leave you with an apt quote:
Â 

**Â Â "Life is really simple, but we insist on making it complicated." - Confucius**

Till next time,

**Nick Singh**
